IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Flight into Space
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, originally called the Computing Tabulation Recording Corporation.
IBM took the name only in 1924 - it was originally a brand used for subsidiaries in Canada and South America.
IBM was founded by the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the eighties of the nineteenth century.
They owned technology such as the famous "slippers", i.e. hours recording the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the company's supervisory board until 1930.
Flint hired Thomas J. Watson, the company’s chief competitor, to help him manage the company.
The leader then shadowed the founders of IBM – an invincible corporate culture and identity is still built on Watson’s ideas.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, started manufacturing and selling all kinds of machines for businesses – from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson ran the company, it doubled its turnover to <0x24>9 million and began its extensive expansion to all over the world.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that after nearly forty years in the chair he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence, developing the first programming language.
In the 1960s, people and computers from IBM helped NASA drive flights into space - to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous man's flight to the Moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "square," which set the computer standard of the time, called IBM 5150 came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold Lenovo’s computer production to China, instead bought the consulting part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and began to fully engage in high-value consulting and services.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the past three years is the concept of Smarter Planet, "smarter planets".
Its aim is to make smart use of technology in even unplanned areas and to improve the situation, for example in transport or city management.
For the area of commerce, IBM recently introduced a platform "Smarter Commerce", which helps traders manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history in the UK as well.
It established its branch in then Czechoslovakia in 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM, the Czech Republic also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Centre for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and there is also a world-class research team dedicated to voice recognition.
