How Travel Prices Have Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
Travel offices at the time sold in the vast majority only trips to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled on holiday to the sea to the NDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi in the Crimea near the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (they fight to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when the possibility of travelling to Yugoslavia was also possible, but then the Yugoslav regime acceded to the West and the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of socialism was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovakians) were not allowed to travel individually freely even within socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or to the Soviet Union, he needed a letter from that country, otherwise the individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to stand in front overnight with a sleeping bag or have a "good friend" in the travel agency.
However, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
In fact, the Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a currency promise it was not possible to obtain financial means (western currency) for the journey to the West.
However, by far the Czechs most often spent holidays in the countryside, which resulted in the large number of chalets and chalets that the Czechs acquired and this habit survives to this day.
The travel of the Czechs has experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989, holidays in the NDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A huge paradox that we are no longer aware of today is that it was not possible for us to travel freely to the present most popular Croatia until 1989, as it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
At the end of the 1990s, visa waivers were abolished in neighbouring Western European countries, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits to Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians could not afford to travel to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to look at it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tours were made in parks in tents, as our then income did not allow us to pay our hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs’ journey at this time was to drive their own food, cans, salads, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech crown, which finally allowed our tourists to freely buy the western currency after many decades.
However, our standard of living and, with it, the average wages have risen, leading to another important moment around 1997.
Due to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have started regularly from 1997 to prepare for trips with charter air connections, making air travel incredibly discounted thanks to the possibility of contracting quantitative discounts compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had visa-free contact with virtually all the developed countries of the world, except the United States, which further facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-evolutionary travel occurred in 2000, when due to significant demand, the first historically direct charter flight to exotics was to Thailand.
From this year onwards, Czech tourists fly direct charter to warm distant countries, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by around 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, symbolizing our post-evolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States canceled the visa for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czech Republic also spent more than half of its holiday abroad (50.3%) for the first time in its history and for the first time in its history, spending more than CZK 15,000 per person on a holiday abroad.
