"The road to Costa Rica is a dream that becomes a reality"
In an exclusive interview for Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the group is ready to offer one of the best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We have been waiting for more than 20 years, but the group itself ensures that the opportunity for them to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
This was said by the bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively to Viva last week from Brazil.
The group is located on the South American continent as part of a tour to celebrate its 20th anniversary and will be on a unique stop in Central America on Sunday 20th.
This day will be performed at 19:30 at the National Stadium together with the angel group The X and national musicians from Las Robertas.
This is a sample of an interview, the entire transcript of which can be found on the La Nación website.
For your Costa Rican fans it is a dream come true. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
The journey to Costa Rica is also our dream, which becomes a reality.
In South and Central America, we are hardly the second time and the experience so far has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation. It's a wonderful country and I believe we'll be able to stay here for a few days.
So we are very happy to be able to bring you our music.
I ask myself, because they literally love the group here, fans are experiencing these days of preparation very intensively.
What do you say to your most ardent supporters?
Thank you for staying with us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that it took us so long.
Some people already talk about the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does it put more pressure on you?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve performed in the last 21 years have come up in the horizon of a few weeks.
We performed a few great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that we got into shape for a concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to this concert.
We love this country, we love to serve, we love the jungle. For both activities Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo. The waves here are incredible.
My friends ride surfing in Costa Rica or to Nicaragua, or to Mexico. These are the best surfing places. And so we learned about Costa Rica, through people who love surfing.
If we look at your tour, you have prepared a huge show with many songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we’ve never played here, we have no limitations that we can’t do.
We will try to perform our best show with a variety of songs. We will try to play a few songs from each album and introduce our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You will never repeat the repertoire.
- Why?
I think that's partly because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to choose which songs we'll play every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven’t played for a long time, we focus on them and we’re also surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that we might have forgotten about them.
So the show is more interesting for us, and that's why I think it's more interesting for people as well.
This tour will celebrate 20 years of art tracks.
When you look back, is it hard to believe everything you have done?
Yeah, I'm sure.
First of all, I don't think any of us could have imagined that we would be in a big rock band and that we would stay in it for more than 20 years.
We are aware of how much we have been given and we are concerned that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We’re lucky to be able to look at the places we’ve always wanted.
We couldn't have gotten better.
What did it mean to you that you were a significant part of the creation of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group in which the greats themselves are represented.
The people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It is surprising that when a movement arises from a group of friends, it does not happen too often.
From time to time, a group is formed in a city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at a time.
We are proud of this and we are honoured to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we're still playing with some.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are lucky that they are all our friends and we are honoured to be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It is also very unusual for a group like yours to stay together and still have the same members after those years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than the usual duration of the group.
I think, firstly, we are all lucky to be still in this world, and secondly, the fact that we are constantly interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends and, thanks to this, we have been able to open up musical paths that leave everyone sufficient freedom to experiment on their own.
We believe in each other, we value each other’s music, and I don’t think it could be better.
Your relationship with the word of glory has not been easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew up, it was gradually becoming easier to find a balance.
We try not to go too far on tour, because it is very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came because of music, you remember that you have to respect music and what you gave it. You must not be robbed by being famous, rock stars. None of us really care about this.
How do you remember the next Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote great songs and at the beginning it was something great.
“We’ve been around as a band for three years and we never released an album until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. The most important thing is that even today we are friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us. When I listen to some other song, I'm not going to look at it like I would, and I remember it.
He was an incredible person and we miss him so much.
Las Robertas will be commissioned to start the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that that's why you chose them as previewers?
Yes, the production sent us videos with a few suggestions and we liked this group the most. That is why we are curious what Las Robertas offer live and must be very fun.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's the question about Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he adds the first thing that strikes him.
Who influences you as a bassist?
A lot of people.
I'm first attacked by Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all night about bass tech I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge even though it is no longer in fashion?
I think we've always felt a little bit apart from the word grunge.
When it comes to grunge, I imagine the bands I mentioned, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana, and all the others that were created at the same time, and if music is still the same today, it's a great thing, because it's the music that's in front of the Mudhoney band and it's worth playing.
At first, your music had a slightly cloudy character and now it’s more positive.
What is the value of this change?
That’s interesting because I feel like there’s a couple of tracks on the new album that are lighter to rank, but there’s also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very cloudy, although they may sound like positive.
At two o'clock, when Ed played it for me, I cried, and the songs are deeply dark.
I think when you grow up and you have some trauma in your life, you lose someone in your family or a friend, these things will start to affect your art and music, and these two songs are exactly what I think.
I also think you can be a happy person and still do cloudy music.
