Fujimori has been hospitalized again for medical tests.
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized in a public hospital on Tuesday, where he will be tested for the muscle loss he suffers in the lower limbs, his nurse said.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who was sentenced to 25 years in prison for human rights violations committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from a number of diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has been operated four times and doctors are currently under control.
MP Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal doctor, told TV channel Canal N that Fujimori will undergo tests within three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases, where they should find out why he suffers and why he loses strength in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga said that in his view Fujimori could get mercy for humanitarian reasons, but the former president himself does not want mercy because he feels innocent.
He was operated on four times because of tongue cancer, lost 18 kilograms, and to these problems were added other disorders such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cysts, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been serving sentences since September 2007 in the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people who were killed by the killing squadron of the army operating illegally in the first years of his government.
