Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome presented details of the plane crash, in which the secretary of the governor, Francisco Blake, and seven others died.
The communications and transport secretariat (SCT) said the results of the crash investigation, in which government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people died, showed that the helicopter had hit the ground with full force, without the pilot's chance to attempt forced landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, the Secretary for Communications and Transport, said that the pilot had noted that the climate conditions allowed flights to take off.
"Parts that appear indicate that the unit has come into contact with the ground several times, the wing has engaged in branches of trees 25 meters from where the unit lost the corpse."
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, therefore it met all the requirements for the transfer of personnel.
In addition, he stated that, on the basis of the investigation carried out in the area of the collision, no components were found on the ground.
"In the search, it was found that parts of the aircraft were not in any other place, so the aircraft crashed on the mainland as a whole.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 people, meeting all the requirements for the transport of passengers.
The terrain shows a slope with a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary made sure that at the moment it is most important to get results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation can take several months or up to one year.
Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the crash, the helicopter of the President’s General Staff was moving at flight speed and the accident occurred on a soft ascent field.
"This information supports the hypothesis that at the time of the accident it was a regular overflight operation," he said.
At the press conference, SCT representative Pérez Jácome named six key investigative points:
Visual flight:
In accordance with the aviation standards, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, that is, the crew must be seen on the ground during the flight.
Meteorological conditions:
Reports in the AICM indicate adequate conditions at the start, according to which the aircraft is moving towards the border, between the DF and the State of Mexico, the visible layers were clouded at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is likely that because of the cloudy, the crew was looking for a lower area and greater visibility to the Cuernavaca Valley.
The location of the collision.
The collision coordinates and the last record of the helicopter from the radar coincide, it is likely that before the collision there was no loss of control or interference with the flight trajectory.
Dispersion of aircraft residues in restricted territory:
The information we have currently available allows us to assume that the collision occurred on the same trajectory and from the side.
The diagram of the displacement of the aircraft's remains indicates that at the time of the impact on the mainland, the helicopter was full.
There were no fires or explosions.
There was no evidence at the scene of the accident that could indicate that there was an explosion or a fire.
The latest results of the investigation show that there may be several contacts with the mainland.
During the field work, the remains of the aircraft were found at an altitude of up to 9200 feet above sea level, the terrain is narrowed, the height of the slope ranges from seven to 30 degrees.
The photographs show footage in which it was likely to break down along the said route.
The information provides elements that seem to suggest that the helicopter could have come into contact with the land in several places.
After careful search in the vicinity of the accident, in an area that is larger than the area of the excavation, no remains of the helicopter were found, which reinforces the assumption that the collision occurred in a condition when the helicopter was still full.
