The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research to discover the gene responsible for obesity in children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the IPN Institute.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research in order to discover the gene causing obesity in children and adolescents. The research called "The genetics of obesity in children and adolescents" will allow for results related to obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Research Medical Unit in Biochemistry at the 21st Century National Health Center, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was established.
This team is based on the support of specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Investav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
Participation in the research can also be made by the general public, with or without authorization. People can come to the participating IMSS sports centres in Valle de México, where they will perform youth tests every week from 8 p.m.
He stressed that the research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Centre (Mexico State) and since October 8, this activity is also carried out at the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Centre (East of Mexico State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children are obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to determine the components and the significance of genetics when it comes to the development of obesity, and to trace risk factors on Mexican children and young people, thereby preventing the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Day of Diabetes, which is celebrated on November 14, he recalled that the aim is to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on the subject.
The questionnaire will also be asked about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He clarified that every Saturday, anthropometric measurements are performed with all participants (weight, height, belt circumference), blood pressure is measured, glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin are determined, and genes are examined (trying to identify the genes that are attached to them).
Cruz López said that this research reflects health care professionals’ concerns about alarming child weight gain.
'Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, only boys had an increase in obesity by 77% and girls by 47%. Also, there was a dramatic increase in overweight,' the IMSS expert said.
He said that one of the reasons for looking for indicators is the assumption that the population of the country differs from the other populations with its genetic history.
The average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in the genes responsible for the onset of diabetes and obesity.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity is commonly explained as the inability to burn excess energy that we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of participants is that they are given an overall assessment of the condition of children, thereby determining whether they have any known overweight or obesity.
He said that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-diabetic conditions.
The information is still confidential, doctors pass it on in writing to parents and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make to prevent their children from getting sick.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause obesity, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle meaning a lack of daily physical activity, a full-day sitting in front of TV, and the use of means of transportation instead of walking on short distances.
Obesity is also caused by a high calorie intake, that is, a higher intake of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
