In his lecture The Technological Cause of Extrusions, which he delivered during the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalts with polymers, which should result in a mixture of asphalt-like characteristics, but at the same time the mechanization of both.
Herrera Nájera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely hot climates, for example in some cities in the north of the country, thus improving functionality and reducing the formation of spills.
He explained that the asphalt, the heaviest part of the oil, is the accumulation of molecules of hydrocarbons, molecules with a large molecular weight called asphaltins, and others with a low molecular weight called maltenes.
The viscoelastic nature of the asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost in solid condition, while at low temperatures the asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to weather conditions and temperatures, the chemical engineering expert warned.
A scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible tiles, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers is the asphalt insert, formed by small stones poured into the asphalt and then pressed.
He stressed that every stone that makes up the insert is poured with asphalt.
When passing cars or creating pressure, it is possible that the forces in the tile are well distributed.
If it were a modified asphalt, it would break down even better, a chemical engineer believes.
He added that the last layer, called a coat, is placed on the asphalt insert, formed by fine stone, i.e. sand also poured into the asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with the wheel of the vehicle, it must have greater mechanical strength than the asphalt insert and must ensure the friction of the road.
Since as part of the stretching will be exposed to a large load, the coat must be sufficiently thick and pay attention to the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor that should be remembered. Especially water has a big influence on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the terrain is wet, the water spreads inside and is difficult to get out, it causes the softening of all the layers of the tile and thus the formation of molds.
He explained that the coating film is the first to be damaged during the formation of the molds and only then there is damage to the asphalt insert. However, the damage does not occur at one point, but it is a slow process that should stop at the first signs with the help of appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in the formation of extrusions, and therefore the thickness of each layer of tile must correspond to the load of vehicles and must ensure that this load cannot be exceeded.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that in terms of asphalt, we still have a lot of work to do and research is at the beginning. For example, asphalt emulsions that are already available on the market in other countries and make it easy to fix applications without having to use high tea.
