“For security reasons, almost a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase the protection of fauna and flora.
The pipeline itself is a long metal hose weighing like the 242 Eiffel, which is not interrupted anywhere by valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project managers rejected it when the Swedes were little eager to see the Russian state-owned company permanently settled on their shores.
“In the event of a failure, we will stop gas flow in less than 1 minute,” says Jens Müller.
In the event of non-sealing, the gas contained in the pipeline will leak into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, since welding was designed so that the opacity arose once every 100,000 years.
The state of the gas pipeline from the outside is checked by the submarine robot drawn by the ship, while the inside of the pipeline is checked by a device that circulates inside.
This 1 meter diameter cigar-shaped device is inserted into the interior of the pipe and is pressed by gas.
The target will provide accurate information about possible deformation of metal parts after three days of travel at 3 m/s.
The long-distance pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without the slightest repair required.
The gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at start and 100 bar at target.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom remains the leader of the group, which holds a 51% stake.
It was joined by German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have set up a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely favourable.
